In France, voting has traditionally been a low tech: voters isolate themselves in a booth and put an oppressive sheet of paper with their elected candidate in an envelope.
After officials have verified the voter’s identity, the voter puts the envelope in the ballot and signs the voting document.
French Electoral Law codifies the approach fairly strictly.
Since 1988, the ballots must be transparent so that voters and observers can see that there are no envelopes at the beginning of the vote and that no envelopes are added except those duly counted from the voting enveloped by the ballot boxes.
Candidates can send representatives to witness each part of the process. In the evening, the votes of volunteers are counted, who are under extensive supervision, and who follow specific procedures.
